Sarah Ophelia Colley Cannon (October 25, 1912 – March 4, 1996), known professionally as her stage character Minnie Pearl, was an American country comedian who appeared at the Grand Ole Opry for more than 50 years (from 1940 to 1991) and on the television show Hee Haw from 1969 to 1991.
She graduated from Ward-Belmont College (now Belmont University), at the time Nashville's most prestigious school for young ladies, where she majored in theater studies and dance.
She taught dance for the first few years after graduating.
Her first stage performance as Minnie Pearl was in 1939 in Aiken, South Carolina.

The following year, executives from Nashville radio station WSM saw her perform at a bankers' convention in Centerville and gave her an opportunity to appear on the Grand Ole Opry on November 30, 1940.

The success of her debut on the show began an association with the Grand Ole Opry that continued for more than 50 years.

In 1956, she made a paid appearance – $3,000, plus expenses – at the kickoff event of the first Alabama gubernatorial candidacy of segregationist George C. Wallace.
She also appeared at an event starting his 1962 candidacy for governor; by that time, his segregationist stance had hardened into the No. 1 issue of his campaign.

On February 23, 1947, Sarah Colley married Henry R. Cannon, who had been an Army Air Corps fighter pilot during World War II and was then a partner in an air charter service.
In 1969 they purchased a large estate home in Nashville next door to the Tennessee Governor's mansion.

In the late 1960s Nashville entrepreneur John Jay Hooker persuaded Cannon and gospel singer Mahalia Jackson to lend their names to a chain of fried chicken restaurants established to compete with Kentucky Fried Chicken.
Final years =
Cannon suffered a debilitating stroke in June 1991, bringing her performing career to an end.
Her death on March 4, 1996, at the age of 83 was attributed to complications from another stroke.
In 1992, she was awarded the National Medal of Arts.
In 2002, she was ranked as number 14 on CMT's 40 Greatest Women in Country Music list.

Minnie Pearl released a number of single records for RCA Victor during the 1950s, including a few duets with Grandpa Jones.
In the 1960s, she moved to Starday Records.
Pearl was back on RCA in 1974 when Archie Campbell and she released a parody record of Loretta Lynn and Conway Twitty's hit "As Soon As I Hang Up the Phone" which received airplay, but did not chart.
